Northern Boulevard (formerly 372 Broadway), north side, between 147th Street (formerly Peroy Street) and 149th Street (Central Avenue), showing the R.R. Parsons Home in 1873. Two other occupants were, one Montgomery, and M.M. Gillam who for mmany years was advertising manager of the New York Herald. This site is now occupied by four and six story apartment dwellings. View No. 2 shows the grounds around the house.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Northern Boulevard, south side, between 147th and 149th Sts., showing in a set of 4 views the R. B. Parsons house of 1873. Samuel Parsons settled in Flushing where he died in 1841. He married Mary Bowne who died here in 1839. Their son Samuel B. Parsons was born at Flushing in 1819. The Samuel S. Parsons house stood in 1839 on large grounds on Broadway Flushing. The street under construction probably is 147th St. The house faces south on Thirty-eighth Ave.
March 1924.
Views 1, 2, 3 and 4.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Northern Boulevard, at the N.W. corner of 147th Street. This house appears on the 1891 atlas by Wolverton, but ownership is not indicated. Note the cone-shaped balcony and the sign in front which reads: Home of Salted Nuts.
P. L. Sperr  April 13, 1927
